  "doc_id": "61387",
  "text": "We compare our method to simple upsampling methods, such as bicubic interpolation. We compare our proposed method to other approaches that utilize an additional intensity image as guidance. Those methods include the Markov Random Field (MRF)-based approach in [CITATION_1] , the joint bilateral filtering with cost volume (JBFcv) in [CITATION_2] , cross-based local multipoint filtering (CLMF) in [CITATION_3] the guided image filter (GIF) in [CITATION_4] , the nonlocal means filter (MRF+NLM) in [CITATION_5] , the variational model (TGV) in [CITATION_6] and fast guided global interpolation (FGI) in [CITATION_7] . In addition, to illustrate the effectiveness of the low gradient regularization, we also compare with GFL0 proposed in Eq. (1). The GFL0 approach is to minimize the l 0 norm of the gradient, which penalizes the nonzero elements equally. The l t 0 norm proposed in our work also penalizes the nonzero elements, but reduces the penalty for horizontal or vertical derivative ±1. Table 1 reports quantitative results in terms of the root mean squared error (RMSE) between ground-truth depth We highlight the best result in boldface We report the error as RMSE in mm and highlight the best result in boldface maps and the results by various depth upsampling methods including ours. From the quantitative results in Table 1 , we observe that the proposed method clearly performs better than the stateof-the-art methods that utilize an additional guidance input for most images and upsampling factors.",
